"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11631"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7488"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9152"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15304"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19127"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35988"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38908"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43304"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44118"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44954"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46850"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60580","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/60580"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 13-year-old boy presents to his General Practitioner (GP) with a history of chronic sinusitis and recurrent chest infections for which he is constantly coughing up copious amounts of yellow sputum. His mother states that he is frequently getting sick and requiring days away from school. On further questioning, the mother states she has very little to do with the health system, opting for a home birth for her son and denying age-appropriate vaccinations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn physical examination, the patient has normal vital signs and is afebrile. He has mild frontal and maxillary sinus tenderness upon palpation with normal transillumination. Auscultation of the chest exhibits diffuse coarse crepitations with some high-pitched inspiratory squeaks and ronchi. Heart sounds are dual with no murmur however are best heard on the right side of the chest. There is no evidence of peripheral oedema.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Tuberculosis","Pulmonary hypertension","Kartagener syndrome","Cystic fibrosis","Granulomatosis with polyangiitis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient in the above stem has \u003Cstrong\u003EKartagener syndrome \u003C/strong\u003Ealso known as primary ciliary dyskinesia (PCD), an incredibly rare inheritable syndrome with a notable constellation of symptoms. These features being dextrocardia, chronic sinusitis (with the formation of nasal polyps), and bronchiectasis. Situs invertus has also been reported in patients with this condition. The pathophysiology of this syndrome is due to a defect which causes immobile cillia within the respiratory tract epithelium and efferent ductules affecting the production of sperm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETuberculosis (TB) \u003C/strong\u003Eis an infectious disease caused by Mycobacterium Tuberculosis. Symptoms associated with Primary TB are that of cough, low grade fever, weight loss and malaise. Key risk factors for TB are that of birth in an endemic country, immunosuppression and HIV.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESymptoms of \u003Cstrong\u003Epulmonary hypertension \u003C/strong\u003Eare relatively non-specific and are diagnosed via echocardiogram. Physical examination may show signs of right heart failure, a right ventricular heave and a loud P2 heart sound.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECystic fibrosis (CF)\u003C/strong\u003E is a disease of exocrine gland function that involves several organ systems and the main clinical effects are chronic respiratory infections and pancreatic insufficiency. It is a differential to rule out given its links with bronchiectasis and chronic sinusitis. Gastrointestinal symptoms predominate in CF with failure to pass meconium, increased appetite and malabsorptive stools with steatorrhoea. Dextrocardia and situs invertus are not seen in cystic fibrosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGranulomatosis with polyangiitis \u003C/strong\u003Eis a rare form of systemic vasculitis involving small vessels. Although any organ may be targeted, the classic triad consists of upper and lower respiratory tract involvement and pauci-immune glomerulonephritis. Upper respiratory tract involvement includes sinusitis, epistaxis and septal perforation whereas lower respiratory involvement includes cough, haemoptysis and shortness of breath.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Situs abnormality in association with lower lobe bronchiectasis should prompt the diagnosis of Kartagener syndrome"],"references":["Tadesse, A., Alemu, H., Silamsaw, M. et al. Kartagener\u2019s syndrome: a case report. J Med Case Reports 12, 5 (2018). https://doi.org/10.1186/s13256-017-1538-2","Naehrig S, Chao CM, Naehrlich L. Cystic Fibrosis. Dtsch Arztebl Int. 2017 Aug 21;114(33-34):564-574. doi: 10.3238/arztebl.2017.0564. PMID: 28855057; PMCID: PMC5596161.","Garlapati P, Qurie A. Granulomatosis with Polyangiitis. [Updated 2021 Dec 7]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557827/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46005"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12220"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46005","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/46005"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-13T07:39:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-13T07:40:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4747"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60580"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonolog